<TITLE> BNP leader accuses AL of slander </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 7 (bdnews24.com)  BNP standing committee member Khandaker Mosharraf Hossain accused the ruling Awami League of slandering his party leaders. He said Sunday that the government had adopted an aggressive propaganda campaign against the opposition just to keep people away from dissent and opposing the government. The senior leader of BNP, main opposition in parliament, said that as the people were reeling under price spiral of essentials and deteriorating law and order, the government was busy maligning the opposition and slandering its leaders. Mosharraf pledged that BNP would soon get nationalists united under their banner and launch popular movement in a bid to resolve people's problems. In a meeting at the Jatiya Press Club commemorating the 53rd anniversary of the Kagmari Conference and Bangladesh's independence in the present context. Maulana Abdul Hamid Khan Bhashani in 1957 had given the clarion call for Bengalis' independence at the Kagmari Conference. Ex-minister Khandaker Mosharraf said criticising failures of the incumbent Awami League that the prime minister had entered into bilateral agreements with India, although Bangladesh would not secure benefits from it. Urging the government to implement its election commitments, he said, "Stop oppressing the opposition and address people's grievances." Mosharraf also spoke out against the ruling party's bid to politicise all government institutions. Barrister Jebel Rahman Ghani presided over and M Golam Mostafa Bhuiyan presented the keynote paper. 
